               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18580510-name-513" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18580510-name-513" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18580510-name-513" type="surname" value="SUTTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18580510-name-513" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>BENJAMIN SUTTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at West Ham. On 22d April, the prisoner came to me, with a young woman, and hired a room of me—Mr. Parker, who was boarding with me, knew the prisoner, and they shook hands, and had some conversation and some drink—the prisoner asked Parker if he would lend him the coat—he said, "I cannot do that, for I want to go to London"—theprisoner went up into the young woman's room with her, and when he came down, Parker had gone to the water closet, and the prisoner took up the coat from a chair, saying that Parker had lent it him, and he would be back in half an hour, as he was going to look after some money—when Parker came in, I spoke to him, and he went to look after the prisoner—this (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) is Parker's coat—it is torn here.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18580510-name-514" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18580510-name-514" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18580510-name-514" type="surname" value="LACEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18580510-name-514" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS LACEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant to Mr. Reardon, a pawnbroker. The pri<lb></lb>soner brought this jacket on 23d April, and pawned it for 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., in the name of John Anderson; I afterwards gave it up to a policeman.</p>
               <p>
